'''Prince Abbas Hilmi bin [[Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim]] bin [[Abbas II of Egypt|Khedive Abbas Hilmi II Bey]]''' ({{Lang-ar|الأمير عباس حلمي بن الأمير محمد عبد المنعم بن الخديوي عباس حلمي باشا الثاني}}) (born 16 October 1941, [[Cairo]]) is an Egyptian and Imperial Ottoman prince and [[Financial adviser|financial manager]]. A member of the [[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]] and the Imperial House of Osman, he is the only son of [[Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim]] and his [[Ottoman Dynasty|Ottoman]] wife [[Fatma Neslişah|Princess Neslişah]], and grandson of [[Abbas II of Egypt|Khedive Abbas Hilmi II Bey]].

==Early life==
Born in Cairo in 1941, Prince Abbas Hilmi was named after his paternal grandfather [[Abbas II of Egypt|Abbas Hilmi II]], the last [[khedive]] of Egypt. Theirs was the most senior male branch descended from [[Isma'il Pasha]], and thus first in the line of succession to the Egyptian throne by virtue of the [[Imperial Firman of 27 May 1866|1866 rules of succession]]. However, those rules were suspended by the British upon their proclamation of a protectorate over Egypt in 1914. Abbas Hilmi II was deposed, and his son [[Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim|Muhammad Abdel Moneim]] lost his place as [[heir apparent]].<ref name="Burke 35">[[#Mon80|Montgomery-Massingberd 1980]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=bnsUAQAAIAAJ&q=Millfield p. 35]</ref> The throne passed to Abbas Hilmi II's uncles [[Hussein Kamel of Egypt|Hussein Kamel]] and [[Fuad I of Egypt|Fuad I]]. The [[Royal Edict of 13 April 1922]] specifically excluded Abbas Hilmi II from the succession, although it stated that "this exception shall not apply to his sons and their progeny."<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rizk |first=Yunan Labib |authorlink=Younan Labib Rizk |date=10–16 February 2000 |title=The fallen dynasty |journal=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]] |series=A Diwan of contemporary life, 324 |issue=468 |url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/468/chrncls.htm |accessdate=9 October 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720043015/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/468/chrncls.htm |archivedate=20 July 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This meant that Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim and his son Prince Abbas Hilmi remained eligible for the throne and retained a senior position in the [[order of precedence]] of the [[Kingdom of Egypt]].<ref>{{Cite book |author=Cabinet of the Grand Chamberlain of the Kingdom of Egypt |title=Protocole |year=1947 |publisher=National Printing House |location=Cairo |language=French |oclc=2482348 |page=22 |trans-chapter=Members of the Royal Family by their degree of proximity to His Majesty the King |chapter=[[:File:Protocole du Royaume d'Égypte, 1947 – Page 022.jpg|Membres de la Famille Royale dans l'ordre de leur parenté avec Sa Majesté le Roi]]}}</ref>

Prince Abbas Hilmi's two great-grandfathers on his mother's side were [[Mehmed VI]], the last Ottoman sultan, and [[Abdülmecid II]], the last Ottoman caliph.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ottomanfamily.com/family_tree.html |title=Ottoman Family Tree |publisher=Official website of the immediate living descendants of the Ottoman Dynasty |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420055333/http://www.ottomanfamily.com/family_tree.html |archivedate=20 April 2008}}</ref><ref>[[#Mon80|Montgomery-Massingberd 1980]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=bnsUAQAAIAAJ&q=Neslisah p. 247]</ref> Had the Ottoman monarchy not been abolished in 1922, Prince Abbas Hilmi would have received, in addition to his Egyptian princely title ({{Lang-ar|أمير|translit=Amir}}), the [[Ottoman titles|Ottoman title]] of ''sultanzade'', which was given to the sons of imperial princesses.<ref name="Sultanzades">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ottomanfamily.com/index.php?page=3 |title=Sultanzades |publisher=Official website of the immediate living descendants of the Ottoman Dynasty |accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref>

In July 1952, the [[Free Officers Movement (Egypt)|Free Officers]] launched a revolution that led to the forced abdication of King [[Farouk of Egypt]] in favour of his infant son [[Fuad II of Egypt|Fuad II]]. Due to Fuad II's minority, Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim was chosen by the [[Egyptian Revolutionary Command Council|new military rulers]] to serve as regent, first as head of a temporary [[Regencies in Egypt|regency body]] and later as sole [[prince regent]]. However, he did not last long in the position, as the Egyptian monarchy was officially abolished on 18 June 1953.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rizk |first=Yunan Labib |authorlink=Younan Labib Rizk |date=27 January – 2 February 2005 |title=Royal help |journal=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]] |series=A Diwan of contemporary life, 578 |issue=  727 |url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2005/727/chrncls.htm |accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> Prince Muhammad Abdel Moneim and his wife Neslişah were arrested in 1957 and accused of taking part in an anti-[[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]] plot.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 December 1957 |title=Egypt Investigates 'Anti-Nasser Plot' |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/12/28/archives/egypt-investigates-antinasser-plot.html |format=Fee required |quote=It said a relative of former King Farouk, Prince Abdel Moneim, and his socialite wife, Nazli Shaa, had been arrested in connection with the plot.}}</ref> Their souring relations with the new revolutionary regime forced them into exile. As a result, their son Prince Abbas Hilmi spent much of his life in England and France.<ref name="Stanford"/>

==Business activities==
{{Egyptian Royal Family}}
Educated at [[Millfield]] school in [[Street, Somerset]], Prince Abbas Hilmi pursued his higher studies at [[Christ Church, Oxford]].<ref name="Burke 35"/> He worked for a [[Discount store|discount house]], a bank and an [[insurance broker]] before joining Grieveson Grant & Co. in 1968.<ref name="Bulletin">{{Cite journal |year=1971 |title=Nothing's really British any more |journal=[[The Bulletin]] |volume=93 |issue=4762–4774 |page=111 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jecXAQAAIAAJ&q=Abbas}}</ref> He remained with Grieveson Grant & Co., one of the [[City of London|City]]'s top stockbrokers, until 1981. In 1970, he made history by becoming the first foreign member of the [[London Stock Exchange]],<ref name="EIMA">{{Cite web |url=http://www.eima.org.eg/prince.asp |title=Prince Abbas Hilmi |publisher=Egyptian Investment Management Association |accessdate=9 October 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012162931/http://www.eima.org.eg/prince.asp |archivedate=12 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> his election having been rendered possible by a change of Rule 21, which had previously restricted membership to British citizens.<ref name="Bulletin"/> After leaving Grieveson Grant & Co., Prince Abbas Hilmi became a general manager of Schroder Asseily & Co. (1981–1983), and then Chairman of Hilmi and Associates (1983–1986), where he was mostly engaged in financial management activities and project finance assignments. After spending three years in London as Vice-President of [[Kidder, Peabody & Co.]] (1986–1989), he joined the Concord Group in 1989, only one year after its establishment.<ref name="EIMA"/> He was part of the three-member team that launched the Concord Group's Cairo office in 1994. Since then, Egypt has become the group's main focus area, with more than half of the assets it manages ($2.8&nbsp;billion out of $3.4&nbsp;billion) being invested in Egyptian [[Security (finance)|securities]]. Concord is currently among the largest [[Investment management|asset management]] firms in Egypt. One of the funds it manages, the Egypt Investment Company Ltd, has been repeatedly ranked by the ''[[International Herald Tribune]]'' as the top performing fund in the world.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Salah-Ahmed |first=Amira |date=13 August 2008 |title=One on One: Concord Carves Niche in Egypt's Capital Market |journal=[[Daily News Egypt]] |url=http://www.dailystaregypt.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=15717 |accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> Prince Abbas Hilmi still works for Concord, where he holds the position of Senior Managing Director.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.concordus.com/bios/ahilmi.html |title=Prince Abbas Hilmi |publisher=Concord International Investments Group |accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref>

==Cultural activities==
Since his return to Egypt in 1994, Prince Abbas Hilmi has devoted considerable time to the conservation of his family's architectural legacy. He was instrumental in providing the funds necessary for the 2004–2008 renovation of his great-grandfather [[Tewfik Pasha]]'s mausoleum, where he has reserved a burial plot for himself.<ref name="Stanford"/> In 2006, he founded the Friends of Manial Palace Museum Association, which seeks to preserve the [[Manial Palace and Museum|palace]] of his granduncle [[Mohammed Ali Tewfik|Prince Muhammad Ali]].<ref>{{Cite journal |date=28 June – 4 July 2007 |title=A princely estate |journal=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]] |issue=851 |url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2007/851/sc15.htm |accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref>

==Marriage and children==
In 1969, Prince Abbas Hilmi married Mediha Momtaz (born 1945). The religious ceremony was performed in [[Istanbul]] on 1 June, and the civil marriage took place at the [[Kensington]] [[Register Office]] in London on 20 June. Mediha is a maternal granddaughter of Ahmad Midhat Abbas Yeghen, a descendant of one of the sisters of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali Pasha]], the founder of the Egyptian royal family.<ref name="Burke 35"/> Prince Abbas Hilmi and his wife Mediha are thus genealogically related, as illustrated by the family tree below. The couple have a daughter, Sabiha Fatma (born 1974), and a son, Daoud Abdel Moneim (born 1979).<ref name="Sultanzades"/> As of 2005, Prince Abbas Hilmi's only sister Ikbal (born 1944) lived in Istanbul with their mother [[Fatma Neslişah|Neslişah]] (1921–2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.egy.com/historica/egyptianconsorts.shtml |title=Egypt's First Ladies |first=Samir |last=Raafat |date=March 2005 |publisher=Egy.com |accessdate=7 October 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922021026/http://egy.com/historica/egyptianconsorts.shtml |archivedate=22 September 2010 }}</ref>

